        <p class="note" style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">
            <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><rect x="3" y="11" width="18" height="11" rx="2"/><path d="M7 11V7a5 5 0 0 1 10 0v4"/></svg>
            <span>Your photos never leave your browser. Everything is read and cleaned on your own device &mdash; nothing is uploaded, stored, or tracked.</span>
        </p>

        <!-- ===== About ===== -->
        <section class="about" aria-labelledby="h-about">
            <h2 class="step-label" id="h-about">About photo metadata</h2>

            <h3>What is EXIF data?</h3>
            <p>EXIF (Exchangeable Image File Format) is information your camera or phone writes into every photo it takes: camera settings, GPS location, timestamps, and device details. It travels with the file wherever it goes.</p>

            <h3>Why remove it?</h3>
            <p>Metadata can reveal where you live, where you&rsquo;ve been, what you photograph with, and when. Stripping it before you share a photo online keeps that information private &mdash; the picture itself is untouched.</p>
        </section>

        <p class="foot">Everything happens in your browser &mdash; your photos never leave your device.</p>
